The Telegraph - Calcutta : International
 Thursday, January 01, 2004 				 China bans appetite spoiler ads
 							 - Friendship and fear mix in march to 2004				 	 The US postal service unveiled four commemorative stamps on Tuesday, that celebrate friendship as portrayed by the Walt Disney studio. The stamps feature several world-famous friends: (clockwise) Goofy, Mickey Mouse and Donald Duck; Bambi and Thumper; Jiminy Cricket and Pinocchio; Simba and his father Mufasa. (AP)																								Beijing, Dec. 31 (Reuters): China is ringing in the new year by banning television advertising for sanitary towels, haemorrhoid ointments and other items deemed unappetising during meal times, the China Daily said today.																								A new regulation...will prevent the broadcasting of advertisements for products such as sanitary napkins and medicine for haemorrhoids and athletes foot during dinner time, as some viewers may consider them to be offensive, the newspaper said.																								The state administration of radio, film and television, which unveiled the restrictions in September, has already set up a hotline for viewers to report violations.																								The new rules, which take effect on New Years Day, also limit the number of ads allowed to interrupt television programmes.																								In 2000, a viewer in Xian sued a pay-cable television station for cutting excessively into a hugely popular soap opera to flash commercials. 																								A local court awarded him 725 yuan ($87).
